Conclusion of the Summit of UNASUR without publication of the Declaration of Lima
The 6th Summit of Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, which was announced previously and should theoretically be signed by the seven present rulers.
Efe tried repeatedly to access the signed document for the VI. Ordinary Session of the Heads of State and Heads of Government of UNASUR to obtain. Sources in the State and President of the Republic told initially that they would pass it to the exam, but afterwards, declared that it would be published some time on the website of the Peruvian government.
For questions about the text, they indicated that the content of the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, has been presented with a short statement to the press.
The access of journalists to provide information on the Summit was restricted at any time.
During the day was in the press room just the image of the President meeting with no sound with the message transfer "private session, limited audio".
The little information that is circulated among journalists, were obtained from the spokespersons of some of the governments of the Unasur present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press secretary.
The only document that was distributed during the day, was the list of participating presidents what caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from different national and international media, which called for more information.
Then the president of Peru sent the media an e -mail with the "Final Declaration" of the summit, but said it involved the explanation of Humala and not the official document at the end of the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the III. Summit South America - Arab Countries (ASPA), and on this occasion, despite insistent demand by the press, the so-called Declaration of Lima, which had been previously announced, nor published.
On the official website of the ASPA you can convince them that the document was released last Tuesday.
On both international meeting stressed the Peruvian authorities that the information systems for the journalists were present, but they were limited to a high degree of access to information.
The summit ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Court of The Hague, which attaches a border dispute between the two countries.
The President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastian Pinera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the ICJ, which begins at The Hague on Monday, in the process, the Lima initiated against Santiago, the to hear arguments on both sides.
"We will comply with and execute judgment upon the differences that we currently put forward this international court," Humala said with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and continues to be a country that adheres to the international laws, peaceful solutions to disputes examined concludes agreements and the international courts subjects," Pinera added and greeted Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of both President that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia after a decision on the maritime border with Nicaragua, which considered it a grave error brought an action against the agreement of Bogotá, in which it agreed to the judge to make such international tribunal.
Present at the summit were the President of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, of Venezuela, Hugo Chavez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and of Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which is excluded since 2011 after the overthrow of its president Fernando Lugo of Unasur, did not attend the meeting.
The host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and ended the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The head of state leaving the final document in which it announced that 16 decisions made and the action lines for 31 projects between the South American countries with a total investment of$ 17 billion have been set.
Among the decisions taken, he said that the countries of Unasur "will make significant steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship, which we expand the decisions on residence rights."
He said that measures would be promoted to "cooperation in the fight against insecurity in the cities and organized to enhance transnational crime, as well as measures to increase access to medicines and to the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America to improve and to act jointly and effectively in the event of natural disasters."
With the crisis in Europe must "accept the economic consolidation triumphant trains (in Latin America), but should serve to expand our production capacity and our people demonstrate a better future," Humala said.
"We have decided to give a series of 31 emblematic projects priority, which should improve the spatial connections in South America and especially in rural and frontier areas... and thus unite our countries and new forms of economic prospects," the president said in a Peruvian picked explanation.
Among these projects were also five Peruvian, which would lie on the transverse axis of its territory from the coast of Brazil, and two of which are designed to ensure a better connection with Ecuador, although he gave no further details.
Similarly, the final document made reference to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the election process in this country is used for its resumption in the Union of South American Nations," of which it is currently excluded.
The need that Latin America continues to be an integrated region of prosperity and peace and good neighborly relations, was another aspect that was emphasized at the summit.
